<br>
My faction with the Crushbone Orcs and with the Indigo Brotherhood begin low (as in, KOS) and are currently at the very bottom (as in, kill-anything-nearby-on-sight).  My faction with the Dwarves of Kaladim is incredibly high (allied, in fact) as it is in Kelethin (duh).<br>
<br>
However, the ideology and philosophy of true neutrality requires that one balance good and evil, not getting involved in the conflicts between races, or between religions, or between good and evil.  This is difficult, since, due to my race and religion, I'm Kill-On-Sight in most &quot;evil&quot; cities.<br>
<br>
It seems to me that it might be interesting to attempt to play a wood elven Druid who sees the schism between the Koada'Dal and the Tier'Dal as balanced, with the Fier'Dal roughly between, but it doesn't seem to me that there's any easy way to build faction in Neriak, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  de facto</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, one's faction tilts towards &quot;good&quot; because the Tier'Dal attack us on sight.<br>
<br>
Anyway, as a player, I simply try to avoid certain racial conflicts--like Grimling vs. Vah Shir, or Dwarf vs. Goblin--in order to maintain my &quot;neutrality&quot;.  I'm just wondering if there might be a more &quot;pro-active&quot; (gagh!  Someone stop me from these buzzwords!) way of maintaining one's putative (there I go again!) neutrality.<br>
<br>
Lasgalen Lothir <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/urobingoodfellow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Robin Goodfellow</A> at: 3/7/02 7:02:39 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/unooneofnote.showPublicProfile?language=EN>NoOneOfNote</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/7/02 7:01:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1507.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Neutrality</span><hr size=1> <br>
Absolute neutrality is really hard to understand and roleplay. It always seems to come off as some weird zen riddle and is fraught with contradictions. But it always seemed to me that most neutrality is not absolute neutrality when you think about it.<br>
<br>
For example in the case of druids they're only neutral in the sense that both good and evil can work against the interests of nature. Thus what would really freak a druid out are rumors of a wizard war, corruption of the land or invasions by undead or demons...all not natural things. The fact that some of those psychopathic Tier' Dal are killing Koada'Dal is just not really that important, just politics. The fact that the Tier' Dal want to kill you is a good reason to avoid them, and you meet the occassional one you can deal with (PC's in other words), but they're not important enough to oppose. And really, when the Koada'Dal get some sort of crazed ambition to &quot;make the world a better place&quot;, and start considering what magics to use, they're almost as dangerous.<br>
<br>
Indeed the fact the Tier'Dal want to kill you just shows they are sadly obsessed with politics and don't realise what is important in the world. That being the natural world on which we all depend.<br>
<br>
That said, I think you could make a decent play on hating those who use un-natural powers. I thought of making a high-elf cleric who will heal everyone except magicians, necromancers and shadow-knights on the basis that pets are an affront against nature <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
That's my take on it anyway, there's lots of others.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uvhoorl.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vhoorl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/7/02 7:37:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1507.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Neutral</span><hr size=1> Try playing a dark elf, and you will see that the roleplayed light races treat you with the same bloodlust the dark elves hold for the light races.<br>
It's just a matter of what camp your in. Both good and evil will scheme, murder and steal in EQ, and call themselves in the right. <br>
<br>
IMO, true neutral would not get the extremes of good and evil involved in their philosophy, since they are identical to one another. <br>
<br>
Rather, a neutral would be concerned with the balance of chaos and law. That is, the existence of the civilized races, and what power they hold in the land, versus the wilderness animal and monster populations, and their power. When one force manifested to an extreme, the neutral would put their efforts toward the aid of the lesser party. <br>
<br>
This is fundamental to how all the mannish races function. It is like the conscious (light) and the subconscious (darkness). Both are required, and have their time so that a being can experience the full range of life. If you snuff out the subconscious, you will never dream, and ultimate predictability, control and entropy (death) would follow. <br>
Likewise if you snuff the conscious, you have a reckless zombie that will upset it's fellow beings.<br>
<br>
Just my thought on neutrality: not an impartial-to-everything attitude, but one that supports a balance of forces. To me, that gives neutral a face, rather than just being a player's excuse to do whatever they feel like because they 'never chose a side'.<br>
<br>
~Vhoorl <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uvhoorl.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vhoorl</A> at: 3/7/02 7:39:17 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=jarmon>Jarmon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/7/02 9:53:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1507.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Neutral</span><hr size=1> Vhoorl hit my thoughts exactly. Playing a true neutral would mean helping the team that was the weakest (and thus support the balance). I think in EQ though, you have to take another look at it. Wood Elf and Halfling Druids in EQ, though labeled &quot;neutral&quot; are basically thrust into the &quot;good&quot; group at least as far as cities are concerned. I look at it from this standpoint: there are MANY more forces of evil in Norrath (counting NPCs of course). Any druid in his right mind would fight against that evil not only to ensure balance but because those blasted dirty evils have no respect for the &quot;foresty&quot; things. &lt;wink&gt;<br>
