How cruel, I plan to put down a rich layer of organic compost in the grand forest of Kelethin in the near future. After all that blood and bone, and perhaps a bit of charcoal from the occasional burning tree-house, is great for plant growth.<br>
<br>
I do agree that most of the neutrals in EQ are basically `good'. The halflings, dwarves and woodelves come from organized, lawful and friendly cultures which are unlikely to have much in common with necromancers and worshippers of evil gods.<br>
<br>
This is especially true since the Dark races would probably exterminate / enslave the good races. Whereas the `good' races might be satisfied with a military victory and not feel the need to completely erradicate the other races. Thus good and neutral are more sympathetic to each other.<br>
<br>
The other type of neutral is `selfish neutral'. People who care about looking after themselves first and will deal with the evil/good question on the basis of what they can get out of it. Likewise the followers of Quellious who might want to `expand their minds' by actively working with evils (which is ultimately selfish).<br>
<br>
The `pure balance' concept of keeping good and evil embroiled in an equal conflict with no chance of victory on either side always strikes me as either an insane or chaotic approach. Followers of rallos zek might want an endless conflict, but it would not make sense for many.<br>
<br>
You'd have things like the druid who successfully protects a village from orcs, and then goes and trains them when they start losing, that's just nuts.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uxianya.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Xianya</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/7/02 10:34:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1507.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Neutrality</span><hr size=1> There are many ways to view neutral. One is seeking a balance between good and evil, another is being apathetic about everything.<br>
<br>
As my character, I view it differently. A kind of a mix. I dont care about the concepts of good and evil. I care about other things. As a druid's concern is nature, whether it be good or evil, I care about my usefulness. I care about my worth to others. And I care about wealth. Okay, so I'm self-centered and maybe a bit spoiled. One day I may come across a group of people being massacred by orcs. I ask if I can help them. If yes, I slay the orcs to the best of my ability. If no, well, hope you all have a happy death. Another day I may come across a group of people planning to ambush or assassinate another group of people. It doesn't matter whoich side of good or evil I fight on, as long as I can help make a difference, and maybe a little bit of cash. <br>
<br>
I do reserve some areas as non-negotiable, such as my guild. My guild is what is most important to me and they will always come first. Order or chaos, good or evil, come what may. Druids have their nature, Warriors have their battles, Cleircs have their dieties. I have my guild.<br>
<br>
