</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 654<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/8/02 7:43:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1507.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> There are many ways ..</span><hr size=1> .. to explain neutrality, but it's basic principal is that you do not choose a side.  As soon as you promote one side over another, you are no longer neutral.  The reason for not choosing is always because you gain more from it than from choosing a side.  The Swiss have been famous for it and if you look at their recent cooperation with freezing terrorist assets, it's really no different than what they've always done: chase the money.  The whole maintaining &quot;good v. evil&quot; balance neutrality is a completely artificial Gygaxism that exists nowhere but in AD&amp;D.<br>
<br>
Anyway, for EQ, Bjond views those that care about &quot;good&quot;, &quot;evil&quot;, and &quot;balance&quot; as religious zealots, fanatics, and crackpots.  He'll listen politely -- much the same way you or I might view the Jehova's Witness or El-Ron worshiper that knocks on your door -- but he'll think you're bonkers.  The only important things are the purity of his art and the fidelity of this relationships.  'Course, it also helps to have many cities beholden to you (ie. have good faction). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ublakkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>blakkon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 211<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/8/02 10:10:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1507.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: There are many ways ..</span><hr size=1> Adding to what Bjond said... <br>
<br>
As far as factions go.  As an order neutral I have it a little easier, I support orderly societies, and disdain the disordly.  However none of my feelings are overt and I judge each individual on their own merits.  As a neutral you do what you have to do, for whatever reasons.  It may be personal advancement, it may be an &quot;adjustment&quot; in the war between good and evil, between order and chaos....  Factions could be roleplayed as an almost incidental result.  In truth Lorec cares not who likes him. He is  a judge (order neutral), but It ill serves him  to be KoS anywhere, as it prevents his studies of the workings of all society and his judgement of the overall balance....  To become KoS to a societyt (read player races) he did not start  out KoS to shows a bias on his part.  I he is   KoS to a society from birth, it shows THEIR prejudice, and he should build faction in order to better know why.<br>
<br>
Like Bjond said.. Pure neutrality is very contrived and doesnt exist anywhere.  If you roleplayed true neutral you would likely  do nothing, fight nothing, unless perhaps it attacked you to begin with. <p>Lorec <br>
